habitat: In herbaceous vegetation on occasionally mown unshaded highway r-o-w at crossing of low spot (broad shallow karst sinkhole) on otherwise level upland underlain by Cretaceous limestone, on soils mapped as deep, well drained, calcareous, moderately alkaline clay (Tobosa Series, Aridic Haplustalfs). Associates included Aphanostephus ramosissimus, Bromus catharticus, B. japonicus, Chamaesyce albomarginata, Elymus elymoides, Engelmannia pinnatifida, Euphorbia spathulata, Gaillardia pinnatifida, Gaura parviflora, Hordeum pusillum, Linum pratense, Matelea biflora, Phlox sp., Senecio tampicanus, Sphaeralcea pedatifida, Tragopogon sp.
locality: S side of highway on S edge of I-10 ca. 2.4 roadmiles E of Taylor Box Rd.

habitat: Calcareous soils. Annual. Population mostly simple-stemmed. The ray florets bright yellow (not sulphur yellow as in var. filifolium). The disc florets mostly yellow in most plants, but some plants with at least brown or brownish disk florets. Similar populations occur along the roadside all the way to Ozona, but shifting by degrees to var. filifolium eastward from Ozona.
